aa(lp30
VThere are a couple of reasons for this that I'll mention to begin with.
p31
aVFirst of all is the misinterpretation of religious scriptures, holy scriptures,
p32
aVin the Bible, Old Testament, New Testament, Quran and so forth,
p33
aVand these have been misinterpreted by men who are now in the ascendant positions
p34
aVin the synagogues and the churches and in the mosques.
p35
aVAnd they interpret these rules to make sure that women
p36
aVare ordinarily relegated to a secondary position
p37
aVcompared to men in the eyes of God.
p38
aa(lp39
VThis is a very serious problem. It's ordinarily not addressed.
p40
aVA number of years ago, in the year 2000,
p41
aVI had been a Baptist, a Southern Baptist for 70 years \u2014
p42
aVI tell you, I still teach Sunday school every Sunday;
p43
aVI'll be teaching this Sunday as well \u2014
p44
aVbut the Southern Baptist Convention in the year 2000 decided
p45
aVthat women should play a secondary position,
p46
aVa subservient position to men.
p47
aVSo they issued an edict, in effect,
p48
aVthat prevents women from being priests, pastors, deacons in the church,
p49
aVor chaplains in the military,
p50
aVand if a woman teaches a classroom
p51
aVin a Southern Baptist seminary,
p52
aVthey cannot teach if a boy is in the room,
p53
aVbecause you can find verses in the Bible,
p54
aVthere's over 30,000 verses in the Bible,
p55
aVthat say that a woman shouldn't teach a man, and so forth.
p56
aVBut the basic thing is the scriptures are misinterpreted
p57
aVto keep men in an ascendant position.
p58
aVThat is an all-pervasive problem,
p59
aVbecause men can exert that power
p60
aVand if an abusive husband or an employer, for instance, wants to cheat women,
p61
aVthey can say that if women are not equal in the eyes of God,
p62
aVwhy should I treat them as equals myself?
p63
aVWhy should I pay them equal pay for doing the same kind of work?
p64
aa(lp65
VThe other very serious blight
p66
aVthat causes this problem is the excessive resort to violence,
p67
aVand that is increasing tremendously around the world.
p68
aVIn the United States of America, for instance, we have had
p69
aVan enormous increase in abuse of poor people,
p70
aVmostly black people and minorities, by putting them in prison.
p71
aVWhen I was in office as governor of Georgia,
p72
aVone out of every 1,000 Americans were in prison.
p73
aVNowadays, 7.3 people per 1,000 are in prison.
p74
aVThat's a sevenfold increase.
p75
aVAnd since I left the White House,
p76
aVthere's been an 800 percent increase in the number of women
p77
aVwho are black who are in prison.
p78
aVWe also have [one of the only countries] on Earth
p79
aVthat still has the death penalty that is a developed country.
p80
aVAnd we rank right alongside the countries that are most abusive
p81
aVin all elements of human rights in encouraging the death penalty.
p82
aVWe're in California now, and I figured out the other day
p83
aVthat California has spent four billion dollars
p84
aVin convicting 13 people for the death penalty.
p85
aVIf you add that up, that's 307 million dollars it costs California
p86
aVto send a person to be executed.
p87
aVNebraska this week just passed a law abolishing the death penalty,
p88
aVbecause it costs so much. (Applause)
p89
aVSo the resort to violence and abuse of poor people and helpless people
p90
aVis another cause of the increase in abuse of women.
