aa(lp92
VLet me just go down a very few abuses of women that concern me most,
p93
aVand I'll be fairly brief, because I have a limited amount of time, as you know.
p94
aa(lp95
VOne is genital mutilation.
p96
aVGenital mutilation is horrible and not known by American women,
p97
aVbut in some countries, many countries,
p98
aVwhen a child is born that's a girl, very soon in her life,
p99
aVher genitals are completely cut away by a so-called cutter
p100
aVwho has a razor blade and, in a non-sterilized way,
p101
aVthey remove the exterior parts of a woman's genitalia.
p102
aVAnd sometimes, in more extreme cases but not very rare cases,
p103
aVthey sew the orifice up so the girl can just urinate or menstruate.
p104
aVAnd then later, when she gets married, the same cutter goes in
p105
aVand opens the orifice up so she can have sex.
p106
aVThis is not a rare thing, although it's against the law in most countries.
p107
aVIn Egypt, for instance,
p108
aV91 percent of all the females that live in Egypt today
p109
aVhave been sexually mutilated in that way.
p110
aVIn some countries, it's more than 98 percent
p111
aVof the women are cut that way before they reach maturity.
p112
aVThis is a horrible affliction
p113
aVon all women that live in those countries.
p114
aa(lp115
VAnother very serious thing is honor killings,
p116
aVwhere a family with misinterpretation, again, of a holy scripture \u2014
p117
aVthere's nothing in the Quran that mandates this \u2014
p118
aVwill execute a girl in their family
p119
aVif she is raped
p120
aVor if she marries a man that her father does not approve,
p121
aVor sometimes even if she wears inappropriate clothing.
p122
aVAnd this is done by members of her own family,
p123
aVso the family becomes murderers
p124
aVwhen the girl brings so-called disgrace to the family.
p125
aVAn analysis was done in Egypt not so long ago by the United Nations
p126
aVand it showed that 75 percent of these murders of a girl
p127
aVare perpetrated by the father, the uncle or the brother,
p128
aVbut 25 percent of the murders are conducted by women.
p129
aa(lp130
VAnother problem that we have in the world
p131
aVthat relates to women particularly is slavery,
p132
aVor human trafficking it's called nowadays.
p133
aVThere were about 12.5 million people sold from Africa into slavery
p134
aVin the New World back in the 19th century and the 18th century.
p135
aVThere are 30 million people now living in slavery.
p136
aVThe United States Department of State now has a mandate from Congress
p137
aVto give a report every year,
p138
aVand the State Department reports that 800,000 people are sold
p139
aVacross international borders every year into slavery,
p140
aVand that 80 percent of those sold are women,
p141
aVinto sexual slavery.
p142
aVIn the United States right this moment,
p143
aV60,000 people are living in human bondage, or slavery.
p144
aVAtlanta, Georgia, where the Carter Center is located
p145
aVand where I teach at Emory University,
p146
aVthey have between 200 and 300 women, people sold into slavery every month.
p147
aVIt's the number one place in the nation because of that.
p148
aVAtlanta has the busiest airport in the world,
p149
aVand they also have a lot of passengers that come from the Southern Hemisphere.
p150
aVIf a brothel owner
p151
aVwants to buy a girl that has brown or black skin,
p152
aVthey can do it for 1,000 dollars.
p153
aVA white-skinned girl brings several times more than that,
p154
aVand the average brothel owner in Atlanta and in the United States now
p155
aVcan earn about $35,000 per slave.
p156
aVThe sex trade in Atlanta, Georgia, exceeds the total drug trade in Atlanta, Georgia.
p157
aVSo this is another very serious problem, and the basic problem is prostitution,
p158
aVbecause there's not a whorehouse in America
p159
aVthat's not known by the local officials,
p160
aVthe local policemen, or the chief of police or the mayor and so forth.
p161
aa(lp162
VAnd this leads to one of the worst problems,
p163
aVand that is that women are bought increasingly and put into sexual slavery
p164
aVin all countries in the world.
p165
aa(lp166
VSweden has got a good approach to it.
p167
aVAbout 15 to 20 years ago, Sweden decided to change the law,
p168
aVand women are no longer prosecuted
p169
aVif they are in sexual slavery,
p170
aVbut the brothel owners and the pimps and the male customers are prosecuted,
p171
aVand \u2014 (Applause) \u2014 prostitution has gone down.
p172
aVIn the United States, we take just the opposite position.
p173
aVFor every male arrested for illegal sex trade,
p174
aV25 women are arrested in the United States of America.
p175
aVCanada, Ireland, I've already said Sweden,
p176
aVFrance, and other countries are moving now towards this so-called Swedish model.
p177
aVThat's another thing that can be done.
p178
aa(lp179
VWe have two great institutions in this country that all of us admire:
p180
aVour military and our great university system.
p181
aVIn the military, they are now analyzing how many sexual assaults take place.
p182
aVThe last report I got, there were 26,000 sexual assaults
p183
aVthat took place in the military \u2014
p184
aV26,000.
p185
aVOnly 3,000, not much more than 1 percent, are actually prosecuted,
p186
aVand the reason is that the commanding officer of any organization \u2014
p187
aVa ship like my submarine, or a battalion in the Army
p188
aVor a company in the Marines \u2014
p189
aVthe commanding officer has the right under law to decide
p190
aVwhether to prosecute a rapist or not,
p191
aVand of course, the last thing they want is for anybody to know
p192
aVthat under their command, sexual assaults are taking place,
p193
aVso they do not do it.
